 I talk to younger and even some older gun owners that claim they're not "into knives".

title: For Sale:  Firearm Hydrodipping: Customize your guns with over 700 brand-name camo's, wood grains, carbon fiber, and more!
location: Fort Collins (contact for location), Fort Collins, Colorado
postcontent:
I run NOCO Hydrographics, a small home business here in Fort Collins doing hydrographic work specializing in firearms. I use only the best quality materials, so you don't have to worry about wear.
I have over 700 films available as well as base coats, so you can pick a custom look to fit your liking. I have brand name camo's such as Kryptek, A-tacs, muddy girl and many others, as well as wood, stone, carbon fiber and metal patterns.
You can view all available patterns here: http://www.watertransferprinting.com/Films.html

I work on anything from AR's to semi-auto handguns, revolvers, shotguns, hunting rifles, you name it. I also do work on automotive parts, as well as ATV plastics. Anything metal, wood or plastic can by hydrodipped.

Hydrodipping is a great way not only to customize your guns, but it will also protect the surface as well as make it easy to identify if it's ever stolen.

Below is a basic pricing schedule, although these are only average estimates to give you an idea and may change depending on the specifics of your job. Feel free to give me a call or email for a closer quote:

Semi-auto handguns: $180
- frame only: $120
- slide only: $80
Revolvers (entire gun): $180
Long Rifles (1 pc. stock, coating barrel and receiver): $250
- Barrel and receiver only: $150
- Stock only: $100
Rifles w/ tactical stocks (AR's, AK's, etc, for covering entire rifle): $250
- furniture excluding receiver: $150

Auto parts or any other miscellaneous items you may be interested in having done will need to be quoted by me.


Jordan Mccullugh- REDACTED Please note the area code is not 970

title: For Sale:  GSG .22 1911
postcontent:
GSG .22 1911 with upgraded parts.  I have replaced a bunch of the plastic stock parts with metal parts to insure that nothing starts to wear on the gun and it cycles better with a tougher spring/ full guide rod (cost me around $75).  

I have also replaced the stock sights with competition style fiber optic front sight (cost me around $75).  

I have 5 magazines that are all 10 rounds (they were $100 for the 3 extra).
I had the slide cerakoted just so that it sticks out from the other GSGs out there.
Comes with attachable rail and fake suppressor.

I'd say I've had maybe 3000 rounds through it and it still shoots great. It's not picky at all on what ammo you run through it but I mainly stuck to CCI mini mag for competition purposes.

Local sale only/ cash only.

German Model 1895/05 K98 bayonet. The standard bayonet used until the end of WW1 by German forces. This bayonet was commonly called the Butcher Blade due to its uncharacteristic blade shape. You see here a model having a sawback as well. These were issued to the pioneer and artillery troops .

This one is in very good condition.  There are a few minor dark spots. But the blade remains in original condition.  The blade has the makers mark of Simpson & Co, SUHL.

Additional markings are: CROWN SYMBOL, W, 16, CROWN SYMBOL LL on the top of the blade between the saw teeth & the hilt. Tiny CROWN SYMBOL LL on the blade side of the hilt. Then, there are two tiny CROWN SYMBOL LL markers near the end of the butt.

The wood grips are in great shape considering they are roughly ONE HUNDRED years old.
In addition, the rivets holding the wood in place have tiny CROWN SYMBOL LL markers.

Buffalo Bore is introducing these three different heavy, yet standard pressure loadings for 38 SPL. title: For Sale/Trade:  Star 9mm 30M Like new, $325, 2 mags, case, loader, manual, clng rod
location: Warren/Sharon to Akron and between, Akron, Ohio
postcontent: This is a modern all-steel pistol with real bluing that I have had since new.  If you miss 15 times, you can still use it to beat the perp to death. I got it quite a while back just when Glocks came out but before the mania.  I was shooting at steel plates at a local club and wanted a reasonably priced double-action high-capacity pistol.  I had confidence in Stars because I have two other Star pistols, which also perform well.  I had no problems with this 30M with a variety of loads.  After a few practices, I decided a 1911 would be better for steel plates because it would be easier to customize.  The Star has been in the safe since then. I never had a holster, so it has no holster wear.  It travelled in the case. It is an all steel, full sized, double stack pistol with rubber grips. It is a commercial version of the military model used by the Spanish military and police.  Star began manufacturing firearms in 1905 and has a history of creating durable practical weapons.  There is a Truth-About-Guns review at http://www.thetruthaboutguns.com/2011/03/benjamin-t-shotzberger/gun-review-star-mod30-m/ with more links and information.  The mags are 15 rounds.  There is an included steel loader as pictured in the box on left side.  Condition is excellent and could pass for new.  It is double action on first shot and single after that.  The safety retracts the firing pin but allows the trigger to lower the hammer.  Rear sights are red dots with a white ramp in front.  The pistol can be ENTIRELY disassembled without tools using its own gun parts, although I never tried it.  It was up for US military adoption and survived mega-round torture tests but lost to Beretta.  New mags are in-stock at Midway for $23.  I read that S&W 5906 mags can be used with small modification.

Transmission was taken out and rebuilt when the engine was put in (Both by Jasper). New locking hubs. New windsheild wiper motor. New fuel lines and fuel sending unit. New steering linkage. Has Flowmaster exhaust. Has been used as a farm/4X4 most of its life so it does have some cosmetic issues but is solid. Few dents and dings and lower body rust. Skid plate and receiver hitch were taken off when we took off the fuel tank to do the line and unit work but they are here and just need to be bolted back on. Wired for trailer brakes. Tachometer added with new engine. A/C stopped working years ago and I never found out what happened or tried to fix it. Speakers are blown. Odometer was not reset with new engine. Hydraulics for the back hatch need replaced. Battery is able to be charged but will not hold long term. I have the parts to rebuild the steering box and to replace the speedometer cable. This was my wife's first truck and we intended to fix it back up but I just don't have the time or money to do it. We hate to see it go but don't want it to sit here and rust.

I've had a couple requests for people just wanting to buy just the engine or transmission.. I'm not parting the truck out, it's one package. If you just need one piece off of it then you are welcome to buy it and part it out, but I don't have that kind of time to try and sell it piece by piece.

There are lots of pictures on our ad on craigslist. http://knoxville.craigslist.org/cto/REDACTED.html

title: For Sale:  Custom Smith & Wesson M&P 9mm (standard)
postcontent:
I have a rarely used Smith & Wesson M&P 9mm (standard size) for sale. I purchased this pistol about a year & a half ago for $550 + tax. I also have an additional $500 invested in aftermarket upgrades + gun smith fees. I switched out the trigger system for an Apex Tactical Duty/Carry Kit. This lightens the trigger pull to 3.5-4 pounds (much lighter than stock) and significantly reduces the pre-travel & over-travel. The actual polymer trigger was replaced by a billet aluminum trigger. Overall a much smoother & precise system ($160 plus shop fees). Aftermarket sights by TruGlo, which are fantastic especially in low light conditions (TruGlo TFO, $150). The slide was refinished with Cerakote which is far more durable coating than the standard melonite finish and adds a richer darker color (Cerakote, $120). The polymer grips are stippled (stand paper feel) which provides far better hold....stock grips on M&P tend to be very slick. Comes with BladeTech adjustable holster ($50). On a side note all the custom work was done by a licensed firearm dealer/gunsmith (West Coast Armory). All said & done you'll be hard pressed to find a more complete & custom M&P. 

Will ONLY deal locally. This will be a by the book transaction (law & order every time!).
